I don't know about guild size but like 5-6 person teams. A 4 man team collapses soon after their first member is incapacitated.

>Water buffalo.
A frontline fighter in an adventuring party should be resilient, strong enough to bear armor and a large shield, and be fast enough to keep up. Being able to hit like a truck is a bonus. Buffalo are big, strong, can move relatively quickly, and are built like tanks. While the rhinos and hippo tougher while also being relatively fast they are a bit big for dungeon delving.

>Armadillo
A support magic user should be tough enough to be in the main battle line since the rest of the party needs them to survive and stick close. They also have to be fast to reach injured allies. Armadillos are well protected and actually remarkable speedy.

>Rat.
Gotta have someone to do the sneaky jobs. Someone who can fit through small spaces, walk silently, and has the dexterity to pick locks and pickpocket. Stereotypical yes, but efficient.

>Almost anything that can fly.
Damage magic users need to stay mobile to get into a good firing position. They also need a good escape route. Good senses are also key so they can identify targets. Almost all birds and flying mammals have some kind of good sense whether it be the sight of a raptor or the echolocation of a microbat. Perhaps an owl is best for their silent flight, eyesight, hearing, and just overall cool factor. An owl would even be able to help the rogue out in some cases.

>Leopard.
It's important to have a dedicated ranged character who doesn't need magic. Contrary to most RPGs, bow use is more based on strength than dexterity. A bare minimum of average eyesight with good night vision is necessary. This role also often taken by a ranger so some tracking and survival skills are good here too. Leopards are very strong for their size, can climb trees while carrying things with ease, have good tracking skills, camouflage, and are adaptable to many environments.
